{
  "doc_id": "46917",
  "text": "In terms of server designs, the general idea of 'capacity reclaiming' has been explored earlier in other contexts. For instance, Lehoczky et al. [CITATION_1] provided a 'slack stealing' algorithm that allows aperiodic tasks to steal slack from periodic tasks. Caccamo et al. [CITATION_2] and Nogueira et al. [CITATION_3] provided CBS algorithms that allow one server to 'steal' another server's budget under EDF scheduling. These approaches, however, do not support compositional scheduling. In addition, their 'reclaiming capacity' includes only idle budget due to an overestimation of tasks' execution times, whereas ours includes the idle budget due to interface overheads as well.",
